There is also no warrant in Aristotle for limiting the means by which Nomina] Definition may be effeeted3 as is done by those Logieians who specify synonyms and etymologies. The latter met-hod indeed seems to have trespassed on the domain of Logic from that of Rhetoric. Nor has it the slightest connection with the former, save by an ambiguity of language. The etymology will in nine cases out of ten declare, not the present meaning of the word, but either one that has become obsolete, or some secondary notion, which may account for the imposition of the name, but which at no time formed, strictly speak- ing, any part of its signification. This holds equally of real objects and imaginary. It is only by an equivocation that “bull-piereer” can be assigned as the meaniny of ‘⁶ centaur,’⁷ or the notions of a swine and a quickset fence be combined into that of ‘⁶ hedgehog.⁷⁷

Definition by synonym, on the other hand, may be one of the means of explaining the signification of a name3 though relatively only, and froin the accidental circum- stance of one word being more familiar to the hearer than another3 in which respect all translations from one language into another are equally nomina] definitions. It is not, however, specially mentioned by Aristonea. As a real definition it is obviously inadmissible, as it neither assigns the cause of a phenomenon nor developes the contents of a notion.
